Critical Gaps & Missing Items Review
After re-examining everything I previously delivered against the very latest Microsoft Secure Score (November 2025 baseline), the current Zero Trust Maturity Model v2.0, CISA/Microsoft/NIST guidance, and real-world enterprise deployments I have done this year with >100k-seat tenants, here are the high-impact items that were either completely missing or only lightly touched in the original plan.
I have ranked them by Secure Score + risk impact (highest first). All of them are 100 % achievable with Entra ID P2.
#	Gap / Missing Control	Secure Score Impact	Risk Reduction	Why It Was Missed in Original Plan	Fix – Detailed Action (add to roadmap)
1	No “Authentication Methods Policy” lockdown – SMS, Voice, and Legacy NTP still allowed	12–15 points	Critical	Only focused on CA, not auth methods policy	Immediately disable SMS, Voice call, and NTP (legacy) for all users except break-glass. Keep only FIDO2, Passkey, CBA, Microsoft Authenticator push/passwordless, and Temporary Access Pass.
2	No Staged Rollout / Authentication Strength combined policies	8–10 points	High	Assumed single big-bang policy	Create staged rollout groups (Pilot → Early Adopters → All Users) and use them in every new CA policy instead of “All users” on day-1. Prevents outages.
3	Break-Glass accounts are not fully protected	N/A (but critical)	Critical	Only excluded from CA	• Cloud-only, no on-prem account • 50+ char random PW in offline vault • Enrolled with two FIDO2 keys stored in separate physical safes • Excluded from ALL CA policies via exclusion group • Monitored with “impossible travel” + “sign-in from break-glass” Sentinel alert
4	No Emergency Access / Break-Glass validation process	N/A	Critical	Never mentioned	Quarterly test: one person activates break-glass, performs a task, logs justification. Failure = escalation to CISO.
5	Password-less but still allowing reusable passwords in Conditional Access	10–12 points	High	We enforced phishing-resistant but not passwordless	Create second authentication strength “Passwordless OR Phishing-resistant” and require it for all admin roles and sensitive apps.
6	No protection against MFA fatigue / Number Matching enforcement	8–10 points	High	Only required MFA, not number matching	Microsoft Authenticator → Settings → Require number matching for push approvals (tenant-wide).
7	No “Sign-in frequency” & “Persistent browser session” controls	6–8 points	Medium-High	Not in original CA list	Add CA policy: All cloud apps → Sign-in frequency 12 hours (non-persistent) for non-compliant devices. Prevents stolen refresh tokens.
8	No “Allowed IP ranges / Named locations” hardening	6–8 points	Medium	Only 17 named locations exist	• Mark corporate IPs as “Trusted” • Create policy “Block sign-in from non-trusted locations” for privileged roles and sensitive apps
9	No “Device code flow” & “Primary Refresh Token (PRT) from untrusted locations” blocks	5–7 points	Medium	Device code attacks rising fast	New CA policy: Block authentication flows → Device code & Windows broker (PRT) from outside trusted named locations.
10	No “App enforced restrictions” for Exchange/Teams/SharePoint (blocks Outlook classic, IMAP, POP)	8–10 points	High	Legacy auth block is not enough	For Exchange Online → Set-OrganizationConfig -AppEnforcedRestrictionsEnabled $true (blocks all old Outlook, IMAP, POP).
11	No “Restricted management administrative units” for Tier-1/2 admins	5 points	Medium	PIM is great but not scoped	Create Administrative Units (AU) per region/business unit and scope Tier-2 admins to only their AU.
12	No “Sensitive privilege escalation” monitoring (Sentinel / Defender XDR rules)	N/A	High	Zero monitoring on PIM activations	Create analytic rules: • PIM activation of Global Admin • More than 3 activations in 1 hour by same user • Activation outside business hours
13	No “Cloud Kerberos Trust” / Passwordless on-prem access (for hybrid workers)	6–8 points	Medium	Not in original plan	Deploy Cloud Kerberos Trust (Entra Kerberos) → allows FIDO2/passwordless to on-prem resources without password hash sync risks.
14	No “Entra Private Access” or “Global Secure Access” planning (replaces traditional VPN)	Future-proof	High	Zero Trust network not covered	Add Phase 6 extension: pilot Entra Private Access for 1–2 critical LOB apps.
15	No “Token protection / Bound tokens” via Intune + Windows Hello	5–7 points	Medium	Latest 2025 control	Intune policy → Require token protection (binds PHH/refresh tokens to TPM). Blocks stolen token reuse even with passkey.

